SIMPLE: fudge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fudge
<hw>Fudge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. F.
<ets>fuche</ets>, <ets>feuche</ets>, an interj. of contempt.]</ety>
<def>A made-up story; stuff; nonsense; humbug; -- often an exclamation
of contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fudge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fudge
<hw>Fudge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fudged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fudging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make up; to
devise; to contrive; to fabricate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fudged</qex> up into such a smirkish liveliness.</q>
<rj><qau>N. Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To foist; to interpolate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That last ⟦ldquo⟧suppose⟦rdquo⟧ is <qex>fudged</qex> in.</q>
<rj><qau>Foote.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fudge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fudge
<hw>Fudge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of soft candy composed of
sugar or maple sugar, milk, and butter, and often chocolate or nuts,
boiled and stirred to a proper consistency.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fudge factor</ent>⟦br⟧
